@RowHouse14 Another element we plan to do (but haven't announced) is to use that 10% to get new customers to Storenvy. Either ads or 10%-off
@RowHouse14 We wrestled with it FOREVER. Lots of sweat and internal debate. And this is what will help us make the marketplace better.
@RowHouse14 10% is what we were always thinking. And to slowly raise it over time would be even more disruptive. So decided to just go it.
@RowHouse14 I totally understand. That's why I went as far as to make the video because it's important and I want everyone to understand too
@RowHouse14 But I know change is hard and it won't work for everyone. But this is good for the platform and community as a whole.
@RowHouse14 We're essentially selling you sales for 10%. Sales you wouldn't have gotten. And you're keeping a lot more than us. Seems fair.
@RowHouse14 An important distinction is that we give you a channel to drive your own sales commission-free which Etsy doesn't.
@RowHouse14 It's corporate. We're the anti-mall. I grew up poor in Tulsa, OK w a single mom. Thrift stores, etc. Couldn't be less corp.
@RowHouse14 We look at ourselves as a mall. And so we compared to retail markup which usually keeps 40-60%.
@RowHouse14 I definitely don't want it to look like a corporate approach. We just surveyed other selling venues for "everything".
@RowHouse14 Also many marketplaces such as Amazon and eBay have higher rates when you consider everything like listing fees.
@RowHouse14 We're of course fans of you being on many platforms if they work for you. In this case, we keyed off of retail markups.
@PaeoniaDrop That's definitely a small part but it really doesn't align our incentives with each other. I want to get paid only when you do.
@kiinopia @PaeoniaDrop @paperforest_ Hey guys! Happy to answer any questions you might have. We spent a lot of time developing pricing.
@RowHouse14 @pulpsushi Hey guys! Happy to answer any questions you might have. We spent a lot of time developing pricing.
